<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12091c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12091c">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12091c"> 91(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 206 days &dagger; <font color="red"><sup><teeny>|a</teeny></sup></font>January 21<font color="red"><sup><teeny>a|</teeny></sup></font> BVM &mdash; Ass / Ag 16 / July 31 / June 30 / May 31 / April 30 / March 31 / Feb 28 / <span class="strike"><span class="striketext">Jan 31</span></span> &mdash; / 197</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Jesus]</font> turned to the apostles &mdash; to me Peter and John &mdash; and said that Mary should appear to them again. &lsquo;There are 206 days from her death unto her holy assumption. I will bring her unto you arrayed in this body.&rsquo; <small> Montague Rhodes James, <a name="APNT" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#APNT"><cite title="source">The Apocryphal New Testament</cite></a> (1924) 199</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Excluding &lsquo;Jan 31&rsquo;, which is cancelled, the total number of days does indeed come to 197. The Feast of the Assumption takes place on 15 August. The feast of the Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary takes place on 15 August; this is 206 days after 21 January (feast of St Agnes, virgin-martyr). </mm> </dd></dl>
